can you train a hurt bird you find in the wild if it is hurt it needs medical attention that you are most likely not qualified to give please contact a licensed wildlife rehabilitator you can find one here http www tc umn edu devo contact htm please under no circumstances attempt to care for the bird yourself there is so much more to rehabilitation than keeping the animal alive until you think it is ready to be released you have to know not only what to feed the bird but how please do not attempt to give the bird any liquid by dropper baby birds can aspirate and die how much and how often you also have to know how to assess the birds general health and condition a baby bird kept in captivity must be taught to recognize and find the type of food it will eat in the wild if it is being hand fed it may not associate the bugs and berries and seeds in nature as being food it must also have the opportunity to exercise its wings a lot so it will be able to fly on or shortly after release when i volunteered at the avian rehabilitation center we kept the rehabilitating fledglings in a large walk in cage with lots of shelves and branches leading from one shelf to the other and down to the ground we would place different types of food in the cage for them as they were being weaned from the hand feeding formula we offered seed meal worms and chopped up fruit no fledgling was released until it was eating on its own had sufficient weight gain had all of its flight feathers in good condition had no sign of diarreah or nasal discharge had clear eyes and could fly at least a few feet in a straight line these are the reasons to get the bird to a licensed rehabilitator they have the training and the resources necessary to do all this in addition to having the permits to do it all legally all native migratory birds in the us are protected under the migratory bird treaty act and you must have the proper permits to have them even for a short time even for good reasons like saving them many other countries also have similar laws regarding their native species wild birds can not be kept as pets Hamster Falconry Breastfeeding Chicken Pet skunk Domestic rabbit Bird Guinea pig Constitution of the Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus Cat Kakapo Mealy Parrot Hunting Terri Schiavo Bird migration Seabird Foie gras Albatross H5N1 Livestock Bat Acorn 613 mitzvot Fancy rat Country parks and conservation in Hong Kong Genetically modified food Kashrut Capercaillie Insulin Hemp Ferret Species Vegetarianism Dog agility Hedgehog Elephant Nurse Trapping Similarities between the Bible and the Qur'an Canary Shrimp farm Archery Insurance Peanut Gliding Tetrapod Peafowl Agriculture Diabetes mellitus Scientology beliefs and practices Condor International Red Cross and Red Crescent Movement Orca Social work Dog Animal rights Fish farming Trademark Bovine spongiform encephalopathy Maize Saruman Food and Drug Administration Taboo food and drink Mosquito Tasmanian Devil Obesity Fox hunting Airport Bird flight GNU General Public License Microchip implant (animal) Garfield Sewage treatment Public domain Vitamin C Rowan Domesticated turkey Contract Gray Wolf Dodo Salad Fingers Migratory Bird Treaty Act of 1918 Barley Domestication Comanche Peregrine Falcon Zoo Copyright Weight training Characters of Naruto 